== Legend == Local folklore recounts that the tumulus was dismantled during the construction of {{ill|Osaka Castle|ja|大坂城|12=draft|12=draft}} under {{ill|Toyotomi Hideyoshi|ja|豊臣秀吉|1=Toyotomi Hideyoshi|12=draft|12=draft}} to procure stones. It is said that attempts to move the large stones caused "supernatural events," leading workers to reconstruct the chamber in its original type<ref name="sankei">{{Cite news|lang=ja|url=https://www.sankei.com/article/20170923-7OVK3BYOH5NBJMWGG2NYLQ7JHY/|title=Attempts to uncover the contents led to disasters? The strange legend of Tsukaan Kofun|newspaper=Sankei News|publisher=Sankei Digital|date=September 13, 2017|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20240422030830/https://www.sankei.com/article/20170923-7OVK3BYOH5NBJMWGG2NYLQ7JHY/|archivedate=April 22, 2024}}</ref>. Wedge marks on the stones confirm attempts to split them during dismantling.
== References == * Uehara Archaeological Investigation Report (Tsukaan Kofun), Kawachinagano City Board of Education, 1998. * ''Kawachinagano City History,'' Vol. 1, 1994.<ref name="sankei" /> * Local intypeational signboard, Uehara Property District, 1997.
